00:14:10,958 --> 00:14:14,694
It turns out that the question here
is whether we have a 1-2 shift,

238
00:14:14,694 --> 00:14:18,709
or a 1-3 shift, or a 1-4 shift,
or a 1-5 shift.

239
00:14:18,709 --> 00:14:24,108
The spectra allow you
to rule out some of these mechanisms

240
00:14:24,108 --> 00:14:29,898
and choose the one that is correct.

241
00:14:29,898 --> 00:14:34,502
The next example in this chapter
has already been discussed

242
00:14:34,502 --> 00:14:39,122
in an earlier chapter about
scalar couplings between

243
00:14:39,122 --> 00:14:42,400
a spin S = 1/2, such as a carbon-13,
and a quadrupolar spin

244
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:45,280
such as lithium-6.

245
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:50,405
Lithium-6 has a spin I = 1,

246
00:14:50,405 --> 00:14:56,265
therefore, it has three possible states,
<i>m = +1, 0 or -1.</i>

247
00:14:56,265 --> 00:15:01,153
Consequently, the neighboring
carbon-13, if there were only

248
00:15:01,153 --> 00:15:06,996
one lithium-6, would be split into
a triplet, with three equal intensities.

249
00:15:06,996 --> 00:15:10,625
This is known
as a non-binomial triplet.

250
00:15:10,625 --> 00:15:15,042
As we have discussed before,
four lithium atoms can make

251
00:15:15,042 --> 00:15:17,820
a tetrahedral structure.

252
00:15:17,820 --> 00:15:22,760
These tertiary butyl groups

253
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:25,888
can attach

254
00:15:25,888 --> 00:15:29,587
not to the corners of the
tetrahedron, but to

255
00:15:29,587 --> 00:15:32,540
the middle of each
of the triangular faces.

256
00:15:32,540 --> 00:15:37,692
At low temperatures,
each carbon-13 will be coupled

257
00:15:37,692 --> 00:15:40,046
to three lithium-6.

258
00:15:40,046 --> 00:15:46,228
This results in a rather peculiar
non-binomial multiplet

259
00:15:46,228 --> 00:15:48,169
at low temperature.

260
00:15:48,169 --> 00:15:51,409
But the situation gets even
more complex if we heat it up.

261
00:15:51,409 --> 00:15:54,189
If we go from low
to high temperature

262
00:15:54,189 --> 00:15:57,259
it turns out
that these groups

263
00:15:57,259 --> 00:15:59,830
can move.

264
00:15:59,830 --> 00:16:03,370
They can hop from
one triangular surface to another.

265
00:16:03,370 --> 00:16:05,420
Or, if you prefer, they stay
where they are,

266
00:16:05,420 --> 00:16:10,211
but it's the lithium cluster
that rotates within the cloud

267
00:16:10,211 --> 00:16:13,211
of carbon substituents.

268
00:16:13,211 --> 00:16:17,185
Whatever the case may be,
it turns out that at 26 degrees Celsius,

269
00:16:17,185 --> 00:16:22,814
we find that each carbon-13 is coupled
not to 3 lithium-6 nuclei, but 4 lithium-6 nuclei,

270
00:16:22,814 --> 00:16:26,650
because all four lithium-6 nuclei, even this
remote one, will at one point

271
00:16:26,650 --> 00:16:30,732
be close to the carbon-13,
and have a scalar coupling.

272
00:16:30,732 --> 00:16:32,155
We see two interesting things.

273
00:16:32,155 --> 00:16:35,098
First of all, the multiplet
becomes more complex.

274
00:16:35,098 --> 00:16:39,432
In addition, the effective scalar coupling,
the splitting

275
00:16:39,432 --> 00:16:43,312
is larger here than it was there.

276
00:16:43,312 --> 00:16:46,558
It is actually reduced
because of the averaging.

277
00:16:46,558 --> 00:16:49,518
So I'd like to summarize
Chapter Four

278
00:16:49,518 --> 00:16:53,837
that Peter Hore
dedicated to chemical exchange,

279
00:16:53,837 --> 00:16:56,341
which seems to be one
of his favorite subjects.

280
00:16:56,341 --> 00:17:02,009
It is indeed one of the key aspects
of modern magnetic resonance.

281
00:17:02,009 --> 00:17:05,690
Chemical exchange effects in NMR
can arise either

282
00:17:05,690 --> 00:17:10,499
from chemical reactions or from
conformational equilibria.

283
00:17:10,499 --> 00:17:15,186
In the slow exchange regime,
NMR lines are simply broadened,

284
00:17:15,186 --> 00:17:17,342
and we can measure
that exchange rates by

285
00:17:17,342 --> 00:17:19,722
looking at the line-widths.

286
00:17:19,722 --> 00:17:24,669
The difference in NMR
frequencies between exchanging spins

287
00:17:24,669 --> 00:17:30,594
can be averaged by fast exchange.

288
00:17:30,594 --> 00:17:35,423
It is the magnitude of delta nu,
that is to say the difference

289
00:17:35,423 --> 00:17:38,776
in the chemical shifts between
the nuclei that are involved

290
00:17:38,776 --> 00:17:40,632
in exchange processes,

291
00:17:40,632 --> 00:17:45,305
relative to the exchange rate constants
that determines whether

292
00:17:45,305 --> 00:17:50,529
the exchange process is
in the slow or in the fast regime.

293
00:17:50,529 --> 00:17:55,656
Chemical exchange effects give
information on rates and mechanisms

294
00:17:55,656 --> 00:18:02,366
of chemical reactions, molecular
rearrangements and internal motions.

295
00:18:02,366 --> 00:18:06,822
Now most comments in Peter Hore's book
refer to chemical exchange

296
00:18:06,822 --> 00:18:11,658
between sites that are distinct
because of their chemical shifts.

297
00:18:11,658 --> 00:18:14,659
But there are other ways
of distinguishing sites.

298
00:18:14,659 --> 00:18:18,917
One of them, for example,
is the quadrupole interaction in solids.

299
00:18:18,917 --> 00:18:22,292
Here, at the Ecole Polytechnique
in Lausanne, we have spent years

300
00:18:22,292 --> 00:18:25,635
determining the spectra
of nitrogen-14 which

301
00:18:25,635 --> 00:18:28,440
is a quadrupolar nucleus
with a spin I = 1,

302
00:18:28,440 --> 00:18:31,379
and has a quadrupole interaction
that ranges

303
00:18:31,379 --> 00:18:33,529
from 1 to about 5 MHz.

304
00:18:33,529 --> 00:18:38,011
We have observed
exchange-broadening effects

305
00:18:38,011 --> 00:18:42,648
between different sites that
are interchanging at very high rates.

306
00:18:42,648 --> 00:18:46,490
When the exchange rate
is, say, 1 MHz,

307
00:18:46,490 --> 00:18:50,117
that means the lifetime is
on the order of 10 to the -9.

308
00:18:50,117 --> 00:18:53,378
That is to say nanoseconds.

309
00:18:53,378 --> 00:18:58,577
Consequently, nitrogen-14 spectra
in solids are sensitive to processes

310
00:18:58,577 --> 00:19:02,346
that occur on a timescale
of about a nanosecond.

311
00:19:02,346 --> 00:19:04,783
It all depends which
nuclei you look at

312
00:19:04,783 --> 00:19:06,671
and in which environments.

313
00:19:06,671 --> 00:19:10,541
Chemical exchange is probably
one of the subjects that will live

314
00:19:10,541 --> 00:19:12,184
for many years to come.

315
00:19:12,184 --> 00:19:16,548
Currently, much attention is
paid to chemical exchange in proteins

316
00:19:16,548 --> 00:19:21,552
and also in DNA, for it has been found
that the well-known double helix

317
00:19:21,552 --> 00:19:24,196
is not as static as it appears,
 

318
00:19:24,196 --> 00:19:27,055
and there are many exchange processes
that are worth studying

319
00:19:27,055 --> 00:19:28,945
in large biomolecules.

320
00:19:29,355 --> 00:19:31,976
Thank you for your attention.
